properties.description: Posted by Jason a converted oregonian newsbox claiming you\'ll be cursed if you bypass the (totally nonfunctioning) security system (broken lock) and look inside. contents may change, but i found a tri-met transit map among the rubbish, crunched up week old papers, milk carton, and dirty sock.

properties.name: Eucalyptus tree slowly rubbing itself to death.
properties.description: Posted by Jason  On one of the most underutilized walkways/shortcuts at SFAI\'s amazing campus, you may find a Eucalytpus growing right up against the cold grey ledge. The gentle breeze sways the tree, rubbing itself against this utterly unyeilding concrete edge, resulting in a not insignificant, and perpetually increasing, (IMHO critical) incision. A must see for any nature vs culture buffs. It also emits a unique sound as this happens.

properties.name: Helena Keeffe's Dial-A-Story Phone Booth
properties.description: Posted by Red76  Franklin and 3rd, oakland, californiaFor Helena\'s contribution to the Cultural District she cataloged a number of libraries from around the country that had telephone numbers in which you could call and hear a librarian reading a short story. The phone booth had vinyl lettering informing guests to the phonebooth as to what these telephone numbers were, and the location of the library in question. Helena placed candles within the phone booth and handed out quarters to people walking through the neighborhood.

properties.name: Sticky LED Graffiti Blobs
properties.description: Posted by Jason  23rd st & 10th ave, new york, nyEyebeam\'s got a graffiti research lab (rad!) they invented some LED blobby things that you can throw up unto stuff. Getting it into a pattern or word would\'ve been a nicer example, but there is a video at that URL above, pretty fun stuff.

properties.name: Street Stallion
properties.description: Posted by Jason   NW 9th & Couch, PortlandThis little stallion has been standing guard on this corner for a few months now. He\'s tied to one of the old original horse ties that still adorn many parts of town. (my buddy is also making and installing his own new horse ties around the city, keep an eye out for them).
